rman factory legislation on debates in the United States, point out the differing contexts of the suffrage movement, compare pacifist and antipacifist reactions of women to World War I, and trace shifts in the feminist movements of both countries after the war. Social Justice Feminists in the United States and Germany provides insight into the efforts of American and German women over half a century of profound social change. Through their dialogue, these women explicate their larger political cultures and the place they occupied in them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aMiddle class womenzGermanyxHistory. 0aMiddle class womenzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPolitical culturezGermanyxHistory. 0aPolitical culturezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aWomen social reformerszGermanyxHistory. 0aWomen social reformerszUnited StatesxHistory. 4aGerman Studies. 4aWomens Studies. 7aHISTORY / Women .2bisacsh1 aSchüler, Anja, eeditor.1 aSklar, Kathryn Kish, eeditor.1 aStrasser, Susan, eeditor.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501718120423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501718120.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG